male.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
The antennal basis is adorned with the spinule groups N1, N2, N3, N4, N5, N6, and N17 on the frontal surface; whereas the groups N7, N8, N10, N11, N12, N13, 
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="16" start="start">N</pageBreakToken>
14, N15, and N16 are present on the caudal surface in female and male (Fig. 11
<normalizedToken originalValue="A–D">A-D</normalizedToken>
). Distal margin of the intercoxal sclerites in P1-P4 bear fine hair-setae (Fig. 11
<normalizedToken originalValue="E–G">E-G</normalizedToken>
). The length/width ratio of Enp3P4 is 2.2, the inner spine is 1.21 times longer than the segment, and the inner margin of BspP4 is naked in female (Fig. 11F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Based on the presence of the group N6 on the frontal surface of antennal basis, the naked inner margin of BspP4, the long caudal rami, and the serrated hyaline membrane on the three distalmost segments of A1 in females, 
<taxonomicName class="Hexanauplia" family="Cyclopidae" genus="Eucyclops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucyclops festivus" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festivus">Eucyclops festivus</taxonomicName>
is not included in the serrulatus-group.
</paragraph>
